<meta charset="UTF-8">
This tag sets the character encoding for your webpage.

What it does: It tells the browser how to interpret the text and characters on your site. UTF-8 is a universal character set that includes almost every character, symbol, and emoji from languages all around the world.

Why it's important: Without this tag, browsers might guess the character encoding incorrectly, leading to garbled text (like seeing "" instead of the intended characters). It's a crucial tag for ensuring your text displays correctly for all users.

<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
This tag controls how your webpage is displayed on mobile devices. 📱

name="viewport": This specifies that you're defining the rules for the browser's viewport (the visible area of the webpage on the screen).

content="width=device-width": This part sets the width of the webpage to follow the screen-width of the device. This means your site won't just be a tiny, zoomed-out version of the desktop site on a phone.

initial-scale=1.0": This sets the initial zoom level to 100% when the page is first loaded. It prevents the page from being zoomed in or out by default.

Essentially, this entire tag is the key to making your website responsive, ensuring it looks good and is readable on all screen sizes, from a large desktop monitor to a small smartphone.

